{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-88ed6ffccca0521a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2508.07375 TurnGuide ===\nTITLE: TurnGuide: Enhancing Meaningful Full Duplex Spoken Interactions via Dynamic Turn-Level Text-Speech Interleaving\nCONTRIB: ['We propose TurnGuide, a novel text-speech interleaved generation approach for end-to-end full-duplex speech language models grounded in natural speech data.', 'We introduce a dynamic turn segmentation framework to address the insertion timing and length challenges of integrating text into double-channel dialogues.', 'We introduce a text-guided dialogue modeling framework that interleaves text and speech generation at the turn level to preserve natural acoustic flow.', 'We demonstrate through extensive experiments that TurnGuide significantly improves the semantic coherence of generated speech and achieves state-of-the-art performance on turn-taking events.']\nABSTRACT: Full-Duplex Speech Language Models (FD-SLMs) are specialized foundation models designed to enable natural, real-time spoken interactions by modeling complex conversational turn-taking such as interruptions, backchannels, and overlapping speech. End-to-end (e2e) FD-SLMs leverage real-world double-channel conversational data to capture nuanced two-speaker dialogue patterns for human-like interactions, but their conversational abilities often degrade compared to pure-text conversation due to prolonged speech sequences and limited high-quality spoken dialogue data. Although interleaved text-speech generation could mitigate this degradation, integrating discrete text tokens into continuous double-channel audio streams could disrupt the precise time alignment required for fluid interaction. To a\n=== 2604.04847 Full-Duplex-Bench v3 ===\nTITLE: Full-Duplex-Bench-v3: Benchmarking Tool Use for Full-Duplex Voice Agents Under Real-World Disfluency\nCONTRIB: ['Authentic human speech with systematic disfluency annotation enables fine-grained robustness analysis across five categories.', 'Self-correction and state rollback scenarios test whether models can recognize mid-utterance intent changes and correctly update downstream API parameters.', 'Multi-step function chaining across four task domains requires sequential API calls with fully deterministic outputs for automatic scoring.']\nABSTRACT: We introduce Full-Duplex-Bench-v3 (FDB-v3), a benchmark for evaluating spoken language models under naturalistic speech conditions and multi-step tool use. Unlike prior work, our dataset consists entirely of real human audio annotated for five disfluency categories, paired with scenarios requiring chained API calls across four task domains. We evaluate six model configurations -- GPT-Realtime, Gemini Live 2.5, Gemini Live 3.1, Grok, Ultravox v0.7, and a traditional Cascaded pipeline (Whisper$\\rightarrow$GPT-4o$\\rightarrow$TTS) -- across accuracy, latency, and turn-taking dimensions. GPT-Realtime leads on Pass@1 (0.600) and interruption avoidance (13.5\\%); Gemini Live 3.1 achieves the fastest latency (4.25~s) but the lowest turn-take rate (78.0\\%); and the Cascaded baseline, despite a perfe\n=== 2603.14877 ===\nTITLE: SoulX-Duplug: Plug-and-Play Streaming State Prediction Module for Realtime Full-Duplex Speech Conversation\nCONTRIB: ['We propose SoulX-Duplug, a bilingual streaming state prediction module that unifies VAD, ASR, and turn detection within a single framework to enable low-latency and semantically informed dialogue state control for modular full-duplex spoken dialogue systems.', 'We release SoulX-Duplug-Eval, a complementary benchmark that extends the Easy Turn testset and Full-Duplex-Bench, promoting more standardized and comparable cross-lingual assessment in future research.', 'SoulX-Duplug achieves streaming turn detection with an average latency of 240\\\\,ms, and a full-duplex spoken dialogue system built upon it outperforms existing systems across multiple evaluation settings, validating its downstream practicality.']\nABSTRACT: Recent advances in spoken dialogue systems have brought increased attention to human-like full-duplex voice interactions. However, our comprehensive review of this field reveals several challenges, including the difficulty in obtaining training data, catastrophic forgetting, and limited scalability. In this work, we propose SoulX-Duplug, a plug-and-play streaming state prediction module for full-duplex spoken dialogue systems. By jointly performing streaming ASR, SoulX-Duplug explicitly leverages textual information to identify user intent, effectively serving as a semantic VAD. To promote fai\n=== 2605.06007 ===\nTITLE: \nCONTRIB: ['An open-source, low-latency web platform for the rapid prototyping and evaluation of full-duplex conversational agents.', 'A JSON-based mechanism that makes persona-conditioned interruption policies first-class configurable objects without modifying source code.', 'An automated end-to-end workflow from live deployment through auto-generated surveys to structured log export.', 'A pilot user study demonstrating that preferred turn-taking policies vary by persona role across the Interpersonal Circumplex.']\nABSTRACT: \n=== 2510.08373 DialoSpeech ===\nTITLE: DialoSpeech: Dual-Speaker Dialogue Generation with LLM and Flow Matching\nCONTRIB: ['We design a data processing pipeline for constructing dual-track conversational datasets to enhance training efficiency and model robustness.', 'We present DialoSpeech, a Dialogue TTS architecture that combines a Language Model, a dual-track token generation mechanism, and a chunked Flow Matching acoustic model for zero-shot, high-quality, and expressive dialogue synthesis.', 'Experimental results demonstrate that DialoSpeech consistently outperforms baselines across multiple metrics.']\nABSTRACT: Recent advances in text-to-speech (TTS) synthesis, particularly those leveraging large language models (LLMs), have significantly improved expressiveness and naturalness. However, generating human-like, interactive dialogue speech remains challenging. Current systems face limitations due to the scarcity of dual-track data and difficulties in achieving naturalness, contextual coherence, and interactional dynamics, such as turn-taking, overlapping speech, and speaker consistency, in multi-turn conversations. To address these challenges, we propose DialoSpeech, a dual-track architecture combining", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b483957f-f443-4a4f-9967-33d535cead71", "uuid": "9d8e72af-25d9-4fab-8eff-5c2173125d16", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T09:56:32.512Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2508.07375 TurnGuide ===\nTITLE: TurnGuide: Enhancing Meaningful Full Duplex Spoken Interactions via Dynamic Turn-Level Text-Speech Interleaving\nCONTRIB: ['We propose TurnGuide, a novel text-speech interleaved generation approach for end-to-end full-duplex speech language models grounded in natural speech data.', 'We introduce a dynamic turn segmentation framework to address the insertion timing and length challenges of integrating text into double-channel dialogues.', 'We introduce a text-guided dialogue modeling framework that interleaves text and speech generation at the turn level to preserve natural acoustic flow.', 'We demonstrate through extensive experiments that TurnGuide significantly improves the semantic coherence of generated speech and achieves state-of-the-art performance on turn-taking events.']\nABSTRACT: Full-Duplex Speech Language Models (FD-SLMs) are specialized foundation models designed to enable natural, real-time spoken interactions by modeling complex conversational turn-taking such as interruptions, backchannels, and overlapping speech. End-to-end (e2e) FD-SLMs leverage real-world double-channel conversational data to capture nuanced two-speaker dialogue patterns for human-like interactions, but their conversational abilities often degrade compared to pure-text conversation due to prolonged speech sequences and limited high-quality spoken dialogue data. Although interleaved text-speech generation could mitigate this degradation, integrating discrete text tokens into continuous double-channel audio streams could disrupt the precise time alignment required for fluid interaction. To a\n=== 2604.04847 Full-Duplex-Bench v3 ===\nTITLE: Full-Duplex-Bench-v3: Benchmarking Tool Use for Full-Duplex Voice Agents Under Real-World Disfluency\nCONTRIB: ['Authentic human speech with systematic disfluency annotation enables fine-grained robustness analysis across five categories.', 'Self-correction and state rollback scenarios test whether models can recognize mid-utterance intent changes and correctly update downstream API parameters.', 'Multi-step function chaining across four task domains requires sequential API calls with fully deterministic outputs for automatic scoring.']\nABSTRACT: We introduce Full-Duplex-Bench-v3 (FDB-v3), a benchmark for evaluating spoken language models under naturalistic speech conditions and multi-step tool use. Unlike prior work, our dataset consists entirely of real human audio annotated for five disfluency categories, paired with scenarios requiring chained API calls across four task domains. We evaluate six model configurations -- GPT-Realtime, Gemini Live 2.5, Gemini Live 3.1, Grok, Ultravox v0.7, and a traditional Cascaded pipeline (Whisper$\\rightarrow$GPT-4o$\\rightarrow$TTS) -- across accuracy, latency, and turn-taking dimensions. GPT-Realtime leads on Pass@1 (0.600) and interruption avoidance (13.5\\%); Gemini Live 3.1 achieves the fastest latency (4.25~s) but the lowest turn-take rate (78.0\\%); and the Cascaded baseline, despite a perfe\n=== 2603.14877 ===\nTITLE: SoulX-Duplug: Plug-and-Play Streaming State Prediction Module for Realtime Full-Duplex Speech Conversation\nCONTRIB: ['We propose SoulX-Duplug, a bilingual streaming state prediction module that unifies VAD, ASR, and turn detection within a single framework to enable low-latency and semantically informed dialogue state control for modular full-duplex spoken dialogue systems.', 'We release SoulX-Duplug-Eval, a complementary benchmark that extends the Easy Turn testset and Full-Duplex-Bench, promoting more standardized and comparable cross-lingual assessment in future research.', 'SoulX-Duplug achieves streaming turn detection with an average latency of 240\\\\,ms, and a full-duplex spoken dialogue system built upon it outperforms existing systems across multiple evaluation settings, validating its downstream practicality.']\nABSTRACT: Recent advances in spoken dialogue systems have brought increased attention to human-like full-duplex voice interactions. However, our comprehensive review of this field reveals several challenges, including the difficulty in obtaining training data, catastrophic forgetting, and limited scalability. In this work, we propose SoulX-Duplug, a plug-and-play streaming state prediction module for full-duplex spoken dialogue systems. By jointly performing streaming ASR, SoulX-Duplug explicitly leverages textual information to identify user intent, effectively serving as a semantic VAD. To promote fai\n=== 2605.06007 ===\nTITLE: \nCONTRIB: ['An open-source, low-latency web platform for the rapid prototyping and evaluation of full-duplex conversational agents.', 'A JSON-based mechanism that makes persona-conditioned interruption policies first-class configurable objects without modifying source code.', 'An automated end-to-end workflow from live deployment through auto-generated surveys to structured log export.', 'A pilot user study demonstrating that preferred turn-taking policies vary by persona role across the Interpersonal Circumplex.']\nABSTRACT: \n=== 2510.08373 DialoSpeech ===\nTITLE: DialoSpeech: Dual-Speaker Dialogue Generation with LLM and Flow Matching\nCONTRIB: ['We design a data processing pipeline for constructing dual-track conversational datasets to enhance training efficiency and model robustness.', 'We present DialoSpeech, a Dialogue TTS architecture that combines a Language Model, a dual-track token generation mechanism, and a chunked Flow Matching acoustic model for zero-shot, high-quality, and expressive dialogue synthesis.', 'Experimental results demonstrate that DialoSpeech consistently outperforms baselines across multiple metrics.']\nABSTRACT: Recent advances in text-to-speech (TTS) synthesis, particularly those leveraging large language models (LLMs), have significantly improved expressiveness and naturalness. However, generating human-like, interactive dialogue speech remains challenging. Current systems face limitations due to the scarcity of dual-track data and difficulties in achieving naturalness, contextual coherence, and interactional dynamics, such as turn-taking, overlapping speech, and speaker consistency, in multi-turn conversations. To address these challenges, we propose DialoSpeech, a dual-track architecture combining", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
